50|$|In physics, {{terahertz}} time-domain spectroscopy (THz-TDS) is a spectroscopic {{technique in}} which the properties of a material are probed with short pulses of <b>terahertz</b> <b>radiation.</b> The generation and detection scheme is sensitive to the sample material's effect on both the amplitude and the phase of the <b>terahertz</b> <b>radiation.</b> In this respect, the technique can provide more information than conventional Fourier-transform spectroscopy, which is only sensitive to the amplitude.|$|E
5000|$|Numerical {{simulations}} of <b>terahertz</b> <b>radiation,</b> which active millimeter wave scanners {{do not operate}} at, have produced mixed results. Researchers at the Center for Nonlinear Studies at Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico have used simulations to show a way that <b>terahertz</b> <b>radiation</b> may affect DNA, however the work was not experimentally verified. With further simulations, the resonant effect was shown to be eliminated when using [...] "reasonable physical assumptions".|$|E
